TY  - JOUR
AU  - Moulin, Hervé
T1  - Serial Cost-Sharing of Excludable Public Goods
PY  - 1994
Y1  - 1994/04/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297983
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 61
IS  - 2
SP  - 305
EP  - 325
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - Under the “Conservative Equal costs” mechanism to produce a non-excludable (one-dimensional) public good, each agent reports his demand. The lowest reported demand of public good is produced and its cost is shared equally among all agents. When the cost of producing the public good is convex, this mechanism is strategy-proof (even with respect to coalitions), anonymous and induces voluntary participation. No other mechanism shares these three properties.When the public good is excludable (its cost still convex), there is a mechanism with the same properties, that everyone prefers to conservative equal costs. This mechanism excludes the agent with the lowest (equal costs) demand from consuming (or paying for) a larger amount of the good, ameliorating the free-rider problem.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297983
ER  - 



